Superstore Performance Story: How Boku Super Mart Used Data to Understand Jan-March sales

Introduction
In 2024, Boku Super Mart wanted to understand one thing clearly what drives its performance across cities, products, and customer behaviors?

The company had strong operations in three major cities Naypyitaw, Mandalay, and Yangon and offered a wide range of products, from food and beverages to fashion and electronics. However, sales patterns were inconsistent, and management needed to know why.

To answer that, we built a performance dashboard that brought together key metrics such as gross income, COGS (Cost of Goods Sold), customer ratings, and payment preferences.

Story of the Data
Every sale tells a small part of a larger story.
For Boku Super Mart, that story included 1,000 customers, different payment methods, and changing purchase behaviors across cities.

The data showed that Naypyitaw was the highest-performing city, while food and beverages were the best-selling product category. Customers preferred paying with cash, and most gave average to good ratings for their shopping experience.

The challenge wasn’t lack of sales it was about finding patterns and meaning in those numbers.

Problem Statement
Despite steady sales, Boku Super Mart struggled with:

Uneven gross income across months.
Lack of clarity on which products and cities drove profits.
Limited understanding of customer behavior and satisfaction.
Difficulty choosing which payment methods to prioritize for marketing and system upgrades.
Solution
The solution was a data-driven analysis that focused on key performance indicators (KPIs):
✅ COGS (by city, product, and payment method)
✅ Gross income (by month and gender)
✅ Customer type ratings and satisfaction
✅ Payment preferences and purchasing trends

Using these insights, Boku Super Mart could make evidence-based business decisions from marketing to stock management.

