Data cleaning involved removing blanks in March income and ensuring accurate COGS values across categories. Gender-based and city-level comparisons were structured for clarity.

Pre-Analysis
Before diving in, the data showed:

A total customer count of 1,000.
Gross income fluctuated monthly, with February being the lowest.
Most customers rated their experience as average (508) or good (481), with only 11 bad ratings.
Cash was the most used payment method, followed by E-wallet and Credit Card.
In-Analysis
1. Monthly Gross Income Trends
January: $5,538
February: $4,629
March: $5,212
Gross income dipped in February, possibly due to seasonal or promotional changes.
2. City Performance
Naypyitaw: COGS $105,304 — highest-performing city
Mandalay & Yangon: around $101,000 each
Naypyitaw’s strong numbers suggest higher demand or better pricing strategy.
3. Product Line Insights
Top Seller: Food & Beverages ($52,498)
Lowest: Health & Beauty ($46,851)
Food drives the highest profit margins, while health products may need targeted marketing.
4. Payment Behavior
Cash: $106,863 — most preferred
E-Wallet: $104,755
Credit Card: $95,969
Cash remains dominant, but the small gap with e-wallets shows a shift toward digital payments.
5. Gender and Income
Males: Slightly higher income in most categories except Food & Beverages and Fashion, where females lead.
This balance highlights an inclusive customer base with shared spending patterns.
Post-Analysis and Insights
Naypyitaw is Boku Super Mart’s strongest market high COGS and steady income.
Food and beverages dominate sales; promotional focus here can boost short-term profits.
Cash payments are still king, but E-wallets are closing in, showing digital adoption growth.
Customer ratings are mostly positive, but Boku should address factors behind “average” feedback to improve loyalty.
Gender-based analysis reveals balanced participation — opportunities exist to personalize promotions for both groups.
